const clientId = 'YOUR_CLIENT_ID';
const guildId = 'YOUR_GUILD_ID';
const token = 'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN';

const client = new Client({
  intents: [GatewayIntentBits.Guilds, GatewayIntentBits.GuildMessages],
});
```

4. Implement the ban command:
```javascript
client.on('interactionCreate', async (interaction) => {
  if (!interaction.isChatInputCommand()) return;

  if (interaction.commandName === 'ban') {
    if (!interaction.member.permissions.has('BAN_MEMBERS')) {
      return interaction.reply({ content: 'You do not have the required permissions to ban members.', ephemeral: true });
    }

    const member = interaction.options.getMember('member');
    if (!member) {
      return interaction.reply({ content: 'Please provide a valid member to ban.', ephemeral: true });
    }

    if (member.id === interaction.user.id) {
      return interaction.reply({ content: 'You cannot ban yourself.', ephemeral: true });
    }

    try {
      await member.ban();
      interaction.reply({ content: `${member.user.tag} has been banned.`, ephemeral: true });
    } catch (error) {
      console.error(error);
      interaction.reply({ content: 'Failed to ban the member. Please check the bot\'s permissions and try again.', ephemeral: true });
    }
  }
});
```

5. Login and start the bot:
```javascript
client.login(token).then(() => {
  console.log('Bot is online.');
}).catch(console.error);
```

6. Replace the placeholders (`YOUR_CLIENT_ID`, `YOUR_GUILD_ID`, `YOUR_BOT_TOKEN`) with your actual values.

7. Run the bot using:
```bash
node index.js
```

Now you have a Discord bot with a slash command for banning members. The bot will only be able to ban members in the specified guild and require the "Ban Members" permission to execute the command.

Here's a simple C++ function that uses the markdown library to convert markdown to HTML. This example uses the cmark-gfm fork of CommonMark, which is a widely used and widely compatible implementation of the Markdown specification.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include "cmark_gfm.h"

std::string markdown_to_html(const std::string& markdown) {
    cmark_gfm_state *state = cmark_gfm_parser_new();
    cmark_gfm_core_options options = {
        .allow_unsafe_headers = 0,
        .allow_attributes = 1,
        .allow_html_blocks = 1
    };
    cmark_gfm_parser_render(state, markdown.c_str(), options);
    std::string html = cmark_gfm_node_to_html(state->document, nullptr, 0);
    cmark_gfm_parser_free(state);
    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string input = "# Hello, World!";
    std::cout << markdown_to_html(input) << std::endl;  // Outputs: <h1>Hello, World!</h1>
    return 0;
}
```

Please note that you need to have `cmark-gfm` library installed and linked in your project. If not, you can download it from https://github.com/gabrielecirulli/cmark-gfm and compile it into a static library.

